        "description": "&ldquo;I don't think I'm easy to talk about. I've got a very irregular head. And I'm not anything that you think I am anyway.&rdquo;&mdash;Syd Barrett&rsquo;s last interview, Rolling Stone, 1971&#160;Roger Keith &ldquo;Syd&rdquo; Barrett (1946&ndash;2006) was, by all accounts, the very definition of a golden boy. Blessed with good looks and a natural aptitude for painting and music, he was a charismatic, elfin child beloved by all, who fast became a teenage leader in Cambridge, England, where a burgeoning bohemian scene was flourishing in the early 1960s. Along with three friends and collaborators&mdash;Roger Waters, Richard Wright, and Nick Mason&mdash;he formed what would soon become Pink Floyd, and rock &rsquo;n&rsquo; roll was never the same. Starting as a typical British cover band aping approximations of American rhythm &rsquo;n&rsquo; blues, they soon pioneered an entirely new sound, and British psychedelic rock was born. With early, trippy, Barrett-penned pop hits such as &ldquo;Arnold Layne&rdquo; (about a clothesline-thieving cross-dresser) and &ldquo;See Emily Play&rdquo; (written specifically for the epochal &ldquo;Games For May&rdquo; concert), Pink Floyd, with Syd Barrett as their main creative visionary, captured the zeitgeist of &ldquo;Swinging&rdquo; London in all its Technicolor glory.&#160;But there was a dark side to all this new-found freedom. Barrett, like so many around him, began ingesting large quantities of a revolutionary new drug,...", 
