    "1401229689": {
        "age_range": null, 
        "author": "Grant Morrison,Various(Illustrator)", 
        "description": "Grant Morrison&rsquo;s best-selling multi-part Batman epic continues with Bruce Wayne&rsquo;s return to Gotham city.A time-spanning graphic novel featuring Bruce Wayne&rsquo;s return to Gotham City to take back the mantle of Batman, written by award-winning writer Grant Morrison and illustrated by a stable of today&rsquo;s hottest artists including Chris Sprouse, Frazer Irving and Yannick Paquette. This is the final chapter of the epic storyline that began in the bestselling graphic novels BATMAN&#58; R.I.P. and FINAL CRISIS in which the original Batman was lost in time.", 
        "format": "Hardcover, 232pp", 
        "image": "93928694.JPG", 
        "isbn": "1401229689", 
        "isbn13": "9781401229689", 
        "listprice": "$29.99", 
        "price": "$18.80", 
        "pub_date": "February 2011", 
        "publisher": "DC Comics", 
        "rating": "4", 
        "review": "An odyssey for one of the most iconic figures in comics stretches from prehistory to the end of time, revisiting and reimagining Batman's mythology through a complex narrative. Writer Morrison and a team of artists pick up from the end of Morrison's Final Crisis and Batman&#58; RIP. Bruce Wayne is lost in time after killing Darkseid, a godlike being of pure evil. Piecing together the memories of his past that he's lost and slowly realizing he's been turned into a human booby trap meant to destroy the universe by Darkseid, Bruce is pulled through eras of Gotham City's history that include confrontations with cavemen, witch hunters, pirates, cowboys, and 20th-century cultists. These adventures culminate in a return to the present where he must rely on his fellow superheroes to save him from Darkseid's curse. Morrison's story is designed to add to Batman's aura as a timeless, mythical hero, but the time jumps and Bruce's amnesia sometimes create an uneven narrative. The story also asks readers to possess a wealth of familiarity with the character's decades-long history, making the book not as accessible to newer fans. Different artists&mdash;all strong, colorful storytellers&mdash;give each time period its own mood. (Feb.)", 
        "reviewer": "Publishers Weekly", 
        "title": "Batman: The Return of Bruce Wayne Deluxe Edition", 
        "type": "Hardcover"
    }, 
